s configuration. But maybe I shouldn't worry too much about it because the Native Image tests probably run with the tracing agent, including test classes regardless of any filters. It’s a bit of a complicated situation!\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Exploring serialization options**\\\\n\\\\nI'm thinking about testing JacksonJsonSerializer's default gzip for large payloads with \\\\\\\"type-in-manifest\\\\\\\" enabled. However, I'm running into the concern of potentially duplicating compression logic. There's a feature related to serializing Java's time module, which already works with Akka module types and Scala vectors. I wonder if I could include payloads that utilize java.time.Instant, LocalDate, or Optional as well! This opens up some interesting possibilities for my serialization approach.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Examining build guidance**\\\\n\\\\nI’m checking the current build.gradle without Akka Stream Typed modules. It seems like adding a test for ObjectMapperProvider could be useful, specifically for \\\\\\\"binding-specific object mapper config supports single quoted JSON read feature.\\\\\\\" This won't affect case classes directly since it involves parsing with Jackson. Given the requirement to modify a \\\\\\\"provided file,\\\\\\\" I think a migration approach might be better due to its value. Testing coverage for dynamic-access call sites looks important too. I should consider how to include the right classes for proper metadata generation.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Reviewing migration options**\\\\n\\\\nI see there's no built-in migration available, which complicates things. I might consider using `akka.serialization.jackson.JacksonMigration`, but that’s an abstract class with no compile or run features. This raises a potential issue about maintaining a one-to-one mapping between dynamic-access report classes and the generated test class files. We’ve ad